While the first mention of events related to the history of the '''Bahá'í Faith in New Zealand''' was in 1846<ref name="Spectator1846">{{cite news| title =Mahometan Schism| newspaper =New Zealand Spectator Cook's Strait Guardian | page =3 near the bottom | publisher = | date =15 July 1846 | url = http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=NZSCSG18460715.2.11 | accessdate = 31 May 2013}}</ref> continuous contact began around 1904 when one individual after another came in contact with Bahá'ís and some of them published articles in print media in New Zealand as early as 1908.<ref name="Dec30">{{cite news | last = Bain | first = Wilhemenia Sherriff | title = Behaïsm | newspaper = Otago Witness | location = New Zealand | page = 87| date = 8 December 1908 | url =http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=OW19081230.2.243&srpos=2&e=-------10-OW-1----0Beha-- | accessdate = 2010-09-10}}</ref> The first Bahá'í in the [[Antipodes]] was Dorothea Spinney who had just arrived from New York in Auckland in 1912.<ref name="Spinney">{{cite encyclopedia | title = Stevenson, Margaret Beveridge 1865- 1941 Baha’i| last = Elsmore | first = Bronwyn | encyclopedia = Dictionary of New Zealand Biography | volume = Online | publisher = New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage | url = http://www.dnzb.govt.nz/DNZB/alt_essayBody.asp?essayID=4S46 | date = 22 June 2007 | id = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> Shortly thereafter there were two converts about 1913 - [[Robert Felkin]] who had met [[`Abdu'l-Bahá]] in London in 1911 and moved to New Zealand in 1912 and is considered a Bahá'í by 1914<ref name="BahaiArohanui">There isn't a definite date Felkin is considered a Baha'i except before 1914 - [http://bahai-library.com/zamir/indexes/aroindexetc.html ''Arohanui''], Introduction by Collis Featherstone.</ref> and Margaret Stevenson who first heard of the religion in 1911 and by her own testimony was a Bahá'í in 1913.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Zealand community — The first New Zealand Bahá'í |work=New Zealand Community |publisher=National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of New Zealand |url=http://www.bahai.org.nz/what_is_bahai/NZ_first.html |doi= |accessdate=2009-09-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217081432/http://bahai.org.nz/what_is_bahai/NZ_first.html |archivedate=17 February 2009 }}</ref> After `Abdu'l-Bahá wrote the [[Tablets of the Divine Plan]] which mentions New Zealand<ref name="ToDP7">{{cite book|author = `Abdu'l-Bahá |authorlink = `Abdu'l-Bahá |year = 1991 |title = Tablets of the Divine Plan |edition = Paperback |publisher = Bahá'í Publishing Trust |location = Wilmette, IL |isbn = 0-87743-233-3 |url =http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/ab/TDP/tdp-8.html.iso8859-1 | pages = 47–59 |origyear = 1916-17}}</ref> the community grew quickly so that the first Bahá'í [[Local Spiritual Assembly]] of the country was attempted in 1923<ref name="info">{{cite web| last = Hassall | first = Graham | title = Clara and Hyde Dunn | work = draft of Short Encyclopedia of the Bahá'í Faith | publisher = bahai-library.com | date = January 2000| url =http://bahai-library.com/hassall_clara_hyde_dunn | doi =| accessdate = 2009-09-28}}</ref> or 1924<ref name="1st">{{cite book| last = Effendi | first = Shoghi | authorlink = Shoghi Effendi |author2=J. E. Esslemont | title = Arohanui: Letters from Shoghi Effendi to New Zealand | publisher = Bahá’í Publishing Trust of Suva, Fiji Islands| year = 1982 | location = Suva, Fiji Islands | pages = Appendix,?? | url = http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/se/ARO/aro-83.html.iso8859-1#gr1 | doi = | id =| isbn = }}</ref> and then succeeded in 1926. The Bahá'ís of New Zealand elected their first independent [[National Spiritual Assembly]] in 1957.<ref name="timeline">{{cite web|title=New Zealand community — Historical timeline |work=New Zealand Community |publisher=National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of New Zealand |url=http://www.bahai.org.nz/what_is_bahai/NZ_timeline.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023184025/http://www.bahai.org.nz/what_is_bahai/NZ_timeline.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2007-10-23 |doi= |accessdate=2009-09-19 }}</ref> By 1963 there were four Assemblies, and 18 localities with smaller groups of Bahá'ís.<ref name="stats">{{cite web | url =http://bahai-library.com/handscause_statistics_1953-63&chapter=1 | title = The Bahá'í Faith: 1844-1963: Information Statistical and Comparative, Including the Achievements of the Ten Year International Bahá'í Teaching & Consolidation Plan 1953-1963| author =Hands of the Cause| author-link =Hands of the Cause| pages = 11, 104–5}}</ref> The 2006 census reports about 2800 Bahá'ís<ref name="census">{{cite journal | last = Nachowitz | first = Todd | title = New Zealand as a Multireligious Society: Recent Census Figures and Some Relevant Implications | journal = Aotearoa Ethnic Network Journal | volume = 02 | issue = 02 | publisher = Ruth DeSouza | location = | date = August 2007 | url = http://www.aen.org.nz/journal/2/2/AENJ.2.2.Nachowitz.pdf | issn = 1177-3472 | accessdate = Sep 9, 2009}}</ref> in some 45 local assemblies and about 20 smaller groups of Bahá'ís<ref name="Kapiti">{{cite web|title=About Us |work=The Bahá'í Community of the Kapiti Coast District of New Zealand |publisher=Local Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of Kapiti |url=http://www.kapitibahai.org.nz/collateral/Kapiti_Welcome.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016043211/http://www.kapitibahai.org.nz/collateral/Kapiti_Welcome.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2008-10-16 |doi= |accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> though the [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] estimated there were some 7400 Bahá'ís in 2005.<ref name="WCE-05">{{cite web| title = Most Baha'i Nations (2005) | work = QuickLists > Compare Nations > Religions > | publisher = The Association of Religion Data Archives | year = 2005| url =http://www.thearda.com/QuickLists/QuickList_40c.asp | accessdate = 4 July 2009}}</ref>

== Beginnings ==

The first mention of events related to the history of the religion was a report in a Wellington newspaper in July 1846.<ref name="Spectator1846"/> These were reprints of an 1845 article in the London ''Times'' which relied on Muslim reactions to the new religion.<ref name="States1977">{{cite book|author=National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of the United States|title=World Order|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sUYlAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=31 May 2013|year=1977|publisher=National Spiritual Assembly of the Baha'is of the United States.}}</ref>

In 1853 there was an event with caused great suffering on Babís ( who Bahá'ís hold as a direct [[Precursor (religion)|precursor]] akin to the relationship between [[John the Baptist]] and [[Jesus]].)<ref>{{cite book
| author=Christopher Buck | editor1=Moshe Sharon | editor-link=Moshe Sharon | editor2= W. J. Hanegraaff |editor3=P. Pratap Kumar
 | title =Studies in Modern Religions and Religious Movements and the Babi/Baha'i Faiths
 |chapter=The eschatology of globalization: the multiple-messiahship of Bahá'ulláh revisited
| chapterurl=http://christopherbuck.com/pdf/Buck_2004_Globalization.pdf
 | publisher =Brill Academic Publishers
 | series =Mumen Book Series, Studies in the history of religions
 | volume =CIV
 | date =August 2004
 | pages =143–173
 | url =https://www.questia.com/library/117757165/studies-in-modern-religions-and-religious-movements
 | isbn = 9789004139046 }}</ref> The Babís were blamed for an attempted assassination of the Shah of Persia. Recent scholarship has identified a fringe element distinct from all the major aspects of the religion, its community and leadership at the time.<ref>[http://bahai-library.com/momen_attempted_assassination_shah The Attempted Assassination of Nasir al Din Shah in 1852: Millennialism and Violence], by Moojan Momen, 2004-03-23</ref><ref name="Religio 12-1">{{cite journal | last =Momen | first = Moojan | title =Millennialism and Violence: The Attempted Assassination of Nasir al-Din Shah of Iran by the Babis in 1852 | journal =Nova Religio: The Journal of Alternative and Emergent Religions | volume =12 | issue =1 | pages =57–82 | date =August 2008 | url = | jstor =10.1525/nr.2008.12.1.57 | doi =10.1525/nr.2008.12.1.57 }}<!--| accessdate = 16 April 2013 --></ref> Nevertheless, coverage in newspapers at the time often echoed the Persian government's view blaming the Babís and Babís in large numbers were in fact executed as a result.<ref>* [http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=NZSCSG18530219.2.5 "English Extracts; Persia"], ''New Zealand Spectator and Cook's Strait Guardian'', p. 3 (near the bottom), 19 February 1853
* [http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=DSC18530222.2.13 "Miscellany; How they punish treason in Persia"], ''Daily Southern Cross'', p. 4, (a bit up from the bottom), February 22, 1853
* [http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=NZSCSG18530319.2.8 "English Abstracts; Persia"], ''New Zealand Spectator and Cook's Strait Guardian'', p. 3, (near the middle), 19 March 1853
* [http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=NZSCSG18530323.2.16 "Miscellaneous; How they punish treason in Persia"], ''New Zealand Spectator and Cook's Strait Guardian'', p. 4, (near the bottom), 23 March 1853
* [http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=NZSCSG18530326.2.10 "English Extracts; Persian Heretics and Executioners"], ''New Zealand Spectator and Cook's Strait Guardian'', p. 3, (near the middle), 26 March 1853
* [http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=OW18530402.2.10 "Persian Heretics and Executioners"], ''Otago Witness'', p. 3, (from the top), 2 April 1853</ref>

Following this initial mention of incidents related to the religion there were several contacts between New Zealanders and Bahá'ís at the beginning of the 20th century. New Zealander [[Wilhelmina Sherriff Bain]] may have met [[Sarah Jane Farmer]], a notable Bahá'í in the United States, (see [[Green Acre]]) in 1904. Whoever her contact was, Bain authored a large detailed article in the ''Otago Witness'' published 30 December 1908 edition<ref name="Dec30" /> about the religion.<ref name="bain">{{cite web | title = Wilhelmina Sherriff Bain (1848-1944) An early advocate of the Baha’i Faith in New Zealand, 1908 | work = | publisher = Antipodean Bahá’í Studies | year = 2009 | url =http://www.abs.org.nz/blog/index.php/2008/12/30/wilhelmina-sheriff-bain-1848-1944-an-early-advocate-of-the-bahai-faith-in-new-zealand-1908/ | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref><ref name="Bain bio">{{cite encyclopedia | title = Bain, Wilhelmina Sherriff 1848 - 1944 - Teacher, librarian, feminist, peace activist, writer| last = Hutching | first = Megan | encyclopedia = Dictionary of New Zealand Biography | volume = Online | publisher = New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage | url =http://www.dnzb.govt.nz/DNZB/alt_essayBody.asp?essayID=3B3 | date = 22 June 2007 | id = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> Other articles followed in 1909,<ref>{{cite news | title = An Eastern Religion | newspaper = Colonist | location = | page = 4 | publisher = National Library of New Zealand | date = 3 March 1909 | url =http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=TC19090303.2.60.1&srpos=2&e=-------10--1----0 | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> 1911,<ref>{{cite news | title = Bahaism -New Religion from Persia "Prophet"'s visit to London | newspaper = Poverty Bay Herald | location = |page=1 | publisher = National Library of New Zealand
| date = 21 October 1911 | url = http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=PBH19111021.2.65&srpos=5&e=-------10--1----0 | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> and 1913.<ref>{{cite news | title = A Prophet of Peace | newspaper = Evening Post | location = |page=12 | publisher = National Library of New Zealand | date = 8 March 1913 | url =http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19130308.2.123&e=-------10--1----0-all | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> It is also known that letters were exchanged in 1910 between a Mildred Burdon of [[Geraldine, New Zealand|Geraldine]] and `Abdu’l-Bahá.<ref name="Dec30" /> [[Robert Felkin]] had met `Abdu'l-Bahá in London in 1911<ref name="BahaiArohanui" /> and in 1912 moved to New Zealand where he helped found the [[Whare Ra]].<ref name="EdneyCollege">Edney, Ken. [http://www.mastermason.com/felkincollege/felkin-bio.htm ''Dr. Robert William Felkim and the S.R.I.A.'']. From the website of the Felkin College of the [[Societas Rosicruciana in Anglia]], [[Napier, New Zealand]]. Retrieved 29 March 2007.</ref> Felkin wrote an article for a New Zealand publication which was published around then too.<ref name="1st" />

Meanwhile, [[Auckland]] resident Margaret Stevenson's sister living in the United Kingdom had sent her a copy of "The Christian Commonwealth"<ref name="timeline" /> which had reported on 'Abdu'l-Bahá's speech in London on 27 March 1911. In 1912 Stevenson rented a room to English Bahá'í Dorothea Spinney - a traveling performer of Greek plays - who had just arrived from New York via Auckland.<ref name="Spinney" /> Spinney's stay was probably brief as she is known to have been in New York in November 1912<ref>{{Cite journal |last = Thompson |first = Juliet | author-link = Juliet Thompson |year = 1947 |title = The Diary of Juliet Thompson |publisher = Kalimat Press |place = Los Angeles |url = http://bahai-library.com/books/thompson/4.html |postscript = <!-- None --> }}</ref> and again in January 1913.<ref>{{cite news| title = Euripides at Wells; Miss Dorothea Spinney Reads "Hippolytus" at Student Gathering. | newspaper = The New York Times. | location = | pages = Magazine Section Part Five, Page SM18 | publisher = | date = 19 January 1913 | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1913/01/19/100249615.pdf | accessdate = 2009-10-04 | format=PDF}}</ref> Following learning from a Bahá'í first hand Stevenson decided to subscribed to [[Star of the West (Bahá'í magazine)|Star of the West]],<ref name="1st" /> an early major English publication of the religion, and officially accepted the religion in 1913. Though Felkin is more known for being involved with other interests, another early Bahá'í, Maurice Chambers, counts Felkin as the Bahá'í through whom he learned of the religion and converted in 1914.<ref name="BahaiArohanui" />

Whoever converted first, there was at least one Bahá'í in New Zealand in 1912 and more shortly thereafter.

