After receiving a compilation on forming Assemblies they then returned to New Zealand in December 1925. They also returned with some dust from the Tomb of Bahá'u'lláh which was placed in New Zealand soil at Stevenson's home in a ceremony held on 14 February 1926. Later in 1926 the Bahá'ís in Auckland were able to properly elect their first Bahá'í [[Local Spiritual Assembly]]. In 1928 there were seven assemblies between New Zealand and Australia - by 1939 the number of assemblies had reduced to 4 but the locations with Bahá'ís increased to 17 and by 1940 the count of assemblies reached 19 while there were still 17 other locations with smaller groups of Bahá'ís.<ref name=JORH2012-Smith>{{cite journal
| last =Smith
 | first =Peter| authorlink= Peter Smith (historian) | editor1=Carole M. Cusack | editor2= Christopher Hartney
 | title =The Baha’i Faith: Distribution Statistics, 1925–1949 
 | journal =Journal of Religious History
 | volume =
 | issue =
 | pages =1–18
 | date =Dec 2014
 | url =http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1467-9809.12207/abstract
 | issn =1467-9809
 | doi =10.1111/1467-9809.12207  | accessdate =Sep 10, 2015}}</ref> In 1931 Keith Ransom-Kehler also visited.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Hassall | first = Graham | editor-last = 'Ala'í | editor-first = Sitarih | editor2-last = Daws | editor2-first = Colleen | title = Hilda Brooks and the Australian Baha'i Community | journal = Association for Bahá'í Studies, Australia | volume = 1989 | issue = | publisher = Association for Bahá'í Studies, Australia| location = | url = http://bahai-library.com/hassall_brooks_australian_bahais | issn = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Mathews | first = Loulie | title = Outposts of A World Religion by a Baha'i Traveler; Journeys Taken In 1933-1934-1935, Accompanied by Edward R. Mathews | publisher = Bahai-Library.com | url = http://bahai-library.com/mathews_outposts_world_religion | isbn = }}</ref> In 1934 Bahá'ís from Australia and New Zealand elected a regional National Assembly<ref name=JORH2012-Smith/> - there were three delegates from Auckland, three from Sydney and three from Adelaide.<ref name="timeline" /> From 1934 to 1939 Stevenson served on the regional National Spiritual Assembly of Australia and New Zealand and then died shortly thereafter in 1941. In 1940 the community held its first season school. In 1947 Alvin and Gertrude Blum left the United States for New Zealand where they lived until 1953 when they pioneered and became [[Knights of Bahá'u'lláh]] for the Solomon Islands.<ref>{{cite news | title = The Baha'i Faith in Solomon Islands have launched three stamps | newspaper = Solomon Star Newspaper | location = | publisher = Tooraj Enayati | year = 2006 | url =http://bahai-library.com/stamps/SolomonIslandsBackground.htm | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref>
In 1948 the first person of [[Māori people|Māori]] descent to accept the Bahá’í Faith was Albert White, who was one quarter Māori. In 1949 the first Persian Bahá'í pioneer, Manoochehr Ala’i, arrived as a student at [[Massey College]].<ref name="timeline" /> In 1953 the first standing [[Hand of the Cause]], the highest appointed position in the religion open to all, [[`Alí-Akbar Furútan]], visited New Zealand.<ref name="stats" /> In 1957 the New Zealand community held its first independent convention to elect its own [[National Spiritual Assembly]] with three delegates from Auckland and two each from Devonport, New Plymouth and Wellington.<ref name="timeline" /> This convention elected the first National Spiritual Assembly of New Zealand. In 1958 Hand of the Cause of God, [[Enoch Olinga]] visited the [[Ngaruawahia]] [[Marae]] and talked with elders and four years later, when Hand of the Cause of God, Dr Muhajir visited, Ephraim Te Paa, a [[Kaumatua]] (Māori elder) from Ahipara converted to the religion. In 1963 with the election of the [[Universal House of Justice]] the Hands of the Cause updated and published a kind of census of the religion. At that time there were four assemblies -[[Auckland]], [[Devonport, New Zealand|Devonport]], [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], [[Wellington]] - and 18 localities with smaller groups of Bahá'ís - see maps.<ref name="stats" /> The story of one convert in 1964 includes her concern for her bi-racial children and despair at the bigotry of interracial marriage among the very minorities her children were members (she being [[Celt]] and married a Māori) when she found this kind of marriage highly accepted among Bahá'ís.<ref>{{Cite book | author = Universal House of Justice | title = In Memoriam | journal = The Bahá'í World | volume = XVIII | publisher = Bahá'í World Centre | pages = 730–1 | year = 1986 | url =http://bahai-library.com/books/bw18/720-748.html | isbn = 0-85398-234-1}}</ref> The members of the National Assembly, who participated in the convention for the first election of the [[Universal House of Justice]], were: Hugh Blundell, John Carr, Margaret Harnish, Linda Hight, Percy Leadley, Phyllis Milne, Jean Simmons, Douglas Weeks, and Terry Stirling.<ref>{{cite book |editor = Rabbani, R. |year = 1992 |title = The Ministry of the Custodians 1957-1963 |publisher = Bahá'í World Centre |isbn = 0-85398-350-X |url = http://bahai-library.com/uhj_ministry_custodians&chapter=7 | page = 411}}</ref> The New Zealand Bahá'í community came to the assistance of refugees in 1979 from the [[persecution of Bahá'ís]] in Iran who were allowed to settle in New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite journal | title = Fond memories of NZ welcome | journal = Immigration Matters | publisher = New Zealand Immigration Service | volume = | issue = | date = July 2004 | url = http://www.dol.govt.nz/PDFs/IMIssue2.pdf }}</ref> Between 1987 and 1989, a further 142 Iranian Bahá'ís settled in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia| last = Beaglehole | first = Ann | title = Refugees - 1970s–2003: refugee groups | encyclopedia = Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand | volume = Online | url = http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/refugees/4 | publisher = Ministry for Culture and Heritage / Te Manatū Taonga | date = 4 March 2009 | isbn = 978-0-478-18451-8 | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref>

== Modern community ==

Since its inception the religion has had involvement in [[socio-economic development]] beginning by giving greater freedom to women,<ref name="iranhistory">{{cite web | last = Momen | first = Moojan | title = History of the Baha'i Faith in Iran | work = draft "A Short Encyclopedia of the Baha'i Faith" | publisher = Bahai-library.com | url = http://bahai-library.com/momen_encyclopedia_iran#9.%20Social%20and%20economic%20development | accessdate = 2009-10-16}}</ref> promulgating the promotion of female education as a priority concern,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Kingdon | first = Geeta Gandhi | title = Education of women and socio-economic development | journal = Baha'i Studies Review | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | year = 1997 | url = http://bahai-library.com/kingdon_education_women_development }}</ref> and that involvement was given practical expression by creating schools, agricultural coops, and clinics.<ref name="iranhistory" /> The religion entered a new phase of activity when a message of the [[Universal House of Justice]] dated 20 October 1983 was released.<ref>{{cite journal |title= The Baha'i Faith 1957–1988: A Survey of Contemporary Developments | first = Moojan | last = Momen |author2=Smith, Peter | year = 1989 | url = http://bahai-library.com/momen_smith_developments_1957-1988 |volume = 19 | journal = Religion | pages=63–91 |doi= 10.1016/0048-721X(89)90077-8}}</ref> Bahá'ís were urged to seek out ways, compatible with the [[Bahá'í teachings]], in which they could become involved in the social and economic development of the communities in which they lived. Worldwide in 1979, there were 129 officially recognized Bahá'í socio-economic development projects. By 1987, the number of officially recognized development projects had increased to 1482. In the modern Bahá'í community of New Zealand the Bahá'ís have multiplied their interests internally and externally. Aside from major themes there have also been individual work done in variety of topics - for example [[post-traumatic stress syndrome]].<ref>{{cite conference | first = Barbara | last = McLellan | title = The Chasm of Belief | booktitle = New Zealand Association for Baha'i Studies conference, 1996 | publisher = Antipodes Baha'i Studies | year = 1996 | location = | url =http://bahai-library.com/mclellan_chasm_belief | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> Additionally the community has continued to advocate with the New Zealand government to speak up on behalf of the persecuted Bahá'ís in Iran.<ref>{{cite journal
 | title =Briefing from the New Zealand Bahá’í community
 | booktitle =Report of the Foreign Affairs, Defence and Trade Committee, New Zealand House of Representatives
 | publisher =Bahá'ís of New Zealand
 | date =24 September 2009
 | url =http://www.iranpresswatch.org/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/Select_Committee_response_to_briefing_11.09.pdf 
| accessdate = Sep 10, 2015 }}</ref>

=== Racism ===

In 1997<ref name="in-society">{{cite web | title = Involvement in society | work = New Zealand Community | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of New Zealand | url = http://www.bahai.org.nz/what_is_bahai/NZ_society.html | doi = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> the Bahá’í community approached the [[Race Relations Conciliator]] with a project to honor the memory of Hedi Moani, an Iranian-born Bahá'í who worked to promote positive race relations.<ref name="in2007">{{cite web | title = Human Rights Commission/Te Korowai Whakapono | work = | publisher = NZ Inter-Faith Network | date = February 2007 |url = http://www.interfaith.org.nz/Webpages/NINN-Feb07.aspx | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> Discussions took place over many months and on 10 December 1998 ([[Human Rights Day]]), the Race Relations Office formally announced that [[Race Unity Day]] would be celebrated in New Zealand on 21 March each year.<ref name="in-society" /> The first awards were in 2001.<ref name="in2007" /> There are reviews of speeches in 2007,<ref name="in2007" /> 2008,<ref>{{cite web | title = Race Unity Speech Award - Finding Common Ground / He Rapunga Tahitanga - National semi finals and finals 2008 | work = Events | publisher = NZ Interfaith Group | date = 17 February 2008 | url = http://www.interfaith.org.nz/Lists/Events/DispForm.aspx?ID=73 | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> and 2009.<ref>{{cite web | title = NZ Bahai Community | work = Race Relations > Te Ngira: The NZ Diversity Action Programme > Participants 2009 | publisher = New Zealand Human Rights Commission | url =http://www.hrc.co.nz/home/hrc/racerelations/tengirathenzdiversityactionprogramme/participants2009/nzbahaicommunity.php | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> National coverage of events with the police was affirmed in 2008.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Speech competition promotes race unity | magazine = Ten One, Community Edition |publisher = New Zealand Police | date = April 2008 | url = http://www.police.govt.nz/tenone/20080328-307/April08Speech.htm | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> In addition to national-scale events various localities have had local competitions - an example was the observance in Whangarei<ref>{{cite web | title = Settlement Support is a winner & Regional winner promoting racial harmony | work = Public Notices and News | publisher = Whangarei District Council | year = 2007 | url = http://www.wdc.govt.nz/resources/13017/public-notices-and-news-2009-04-07.pdf | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> and Lower Hutt in 2009.<ref>{{cite web | title = Race Unity Speech Award | work = | publisher = Lower Hutt Bahá'í Local Spiritual Assembly | url = http://www.huttbahai.org.nz/default.aspx?Page=134 | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> In 2012 then 13 year old Rima Shenoy submitted a video that won first place in the [[Race Unity Speech Awards]] of the New Zealand Police and the Bahá'ís.<ref>{{cite web
 | title =Race Unity Speech Awards go from strength to strength
 | publisher =New Zealand Police
 | date =18 June 2012
 | url =http://www.police.govt.nz/news/release/31924 
 | accessdate =Sep 10, 2015 }}</ref>

=== Development ===

As the Bahá'í community has grown in size and complexity it has also run into controversies and survived. In the 1980s there was a controversy about the status of women not being electable to the Universal House of Justice.<ref>{{cite web | last = Universal House of Justice | first = | authorlink = Universal House of Justice | title = 1988 Letter to the National Spiritual Assembly of the Baha'is of New Zealand | work = Letters from the Universal House of Justice, unpublished | publisher = Bahai-Library.com | date = 31 May 1988 | url =http://bahai-library.com/uhj_women_uhj | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref><ref name="momen">{{cite journal | last = Momen | first = Moojan | title = Marginality and Apostasy in the Baha'i Community | journal = [[Religion (journal)|Religion]] | volume = 37 | issue = 03 | pages =187–209 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | date = 8 June 2007 | url = http://bahai-library.com/momen_marginalitiy_apostasy | issn = 0048-721X | doi = 10.1016/j.religion.2007.06.008 | id = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> In 1989 there was a controversy over the burial of a Māori Bahá'í, Pakaka Tawhai. Though the National Assembly had consulted with Tawhai's wife about burial, Pakaka's tribal family, the [[Ngati Porou]], confronted the Bahá'ís during the [[tangihanga]], demanding to take his body back to [[Ruatoria]]. Ultimately they failed.<ref>{{cite web | author = National Spiritual Assembly of New Zealand | title = Special Report on Baha'i Burial vs. Maori Custom | work = Letters from National Spiritual Assemblies, unpublished | publisher = Bahai-Library.com | date = 6 October 1989 | url = http://bahai-library.com/nsa_maori_burial | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> Then member of the [[Universal House of Justice]] [[Peter Khan]] spoke at a conference in New Zealand in 2000, noting that the Universal House of Justice had received letters "written in distasteful language" from New Zealand - he encouraged systematic education of children, application of a moral life, a serious study of the [[Covenant of Bahá'u'lláh]], and study of the writings of [[Shoghi Effendi]].<ref name="khan">{{cite web | last = Khan | first = Peter | authorlink = Peter Khan | title = Dr. Khan's Address at Queen's Birthday Weekend Conference | work = Informal Talks by Notable Figures | publisher = Bahai-Library.com | date = June 2008 | url = http://bahai-library.com/khan_queens_birthday | doi = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref>

Beyond controversies, the Bahá'ís in New Zealand have broadened their interests both through individual initiatives and collective action. In 1991 an assembly was elected in the [[Kapiti Coast District]].<ref name="Kapiti" /> In 2000 two Bahá'í pioneers from New Zealand settled in [[Pitcairn Islands]], one of the few nations on earth that had no Bahá'í presence.<ref name="khan" /> In 2006 Bahá'ís helped dedicate the temporary Spiritual Centre at [[Middlemore Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Spiritual Centre Opens at Middlemore Hospital | newspaper = Project Excel 20-20 Newsletter | location = | publisher = Counties Manukau District Health Board | date = March 2006 | url =http://www.cmdhb.govt.nz/Towards2020/Newsletters/2006/Issue-Mar-2006.pdf | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> In 2007 Dunedin Bahá'ís had been granted access to a community center.<ref>{{cite web | title = Resource Consent Application | work = | publisher = Dunedin Hearings Committee | date = 12 February 2007 | url =http://www.dunedin.govt.nz/__data/assets/pdf_file/0008/26495/RMA-2006-0997.pdf | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> The Universal House of Justice called for a regional conference for the Bahá'ís from New Zealand, the Cook Islands, Fiji, Hawaii, Kiribati, New Caledonia and the Loyalty Islands, Samoa, Tonga, Tuvalu, and Vanuatu to be held in Auckland’s [[Manukau City]], on the sacred grounds of their [[marae]], in 2008 and it came to pass in February 2009.<ref>{{cite news | last = Bahá'í International Community | first = | authorlink = Bahá'í International Community | title = The Auckland Regional Conference | newspaper = Bahá'í International News Service | location = | date = 1 February 2009 | url = http://news.bahai.org/community-news/regional-conferences/auckland.html | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> The ''Bahá'í on Air'' television show is broadcast weekly on Auckland's [[Triangle TV]] which also covers the Cook Islands, American Samoa, and Adelaide, Australia.<ref>{{cite web | title = Resources | work = | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of New Zealand | url = http://www.bahai.org.nz/resources.html | doi = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> There has also been an independent documentary by a non-Bahá'í New Zealander exploring the religion in 2007.<ref>{{cite web | last = Odess-Gillett | first = Warren | title = A Baha’i Perspective 08.15.2009 Warren Odess-Gillett interviews Jess Firth | work =  | publisher = WXOJ-LP | url = http://www.valleyfreeradio.org/2009/08/a-bahai-perspective-08-15-2009/ | accessdate = 2009-09-19 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110722212640/http://www.valleyfreeradio.org/2009/08/a-bahai-perspective-08-15-2009/ | archive-date = 22 July 2011 | dead-url = yes | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 2011 Bahá'ís participated in the community memorial for those who had died in the [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news
 | title = Christchurch Memorial Service
 | newspaper = ESL News New Zealand
 | location = Christchurch, New Zealand
 | date =March 18, 2011
 | url =http://eslnews.org.nz/?p=2685
| accessdate = Sep 10, 2015}}</ref> It was mentioned in a review of spirituality in business in 2012.<ref>{{cite journal
| author1=Luk Bouckaert  | author2= László Zsolnai
 | title =Spirituality and business: An interdisciplinary overview
 | journal =Society and Economy
 | volume =34
 | issue =3
