| accessdate = Sep 10, 2015}}</ref>

=== Demographics ===

A 1999 report from the census bureau noted that of the citizens of New Zealand of Middle Eastern ethnicity, 4% were Bahá'í and 20% of the Bahá'ís in New Zealand are members of some ethnic minority.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Thomson |first=Barbara |title=Ethnic Diversity in New Zealand: a Statistical Profile |journal=Ethnic Affairs Service Information Series |volume=03 |issue= |pages=178, 183 |publisher=Research Unit, Department of Internal Affairs |location= |url=http://www.ethnicaffairs.govt.nz/oeawebsite.nsf/wpg_url/Resources-Research-Index/$file/EthnicDiversity.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014200352/http://www.ethnicaffairs.govt.nz/oeawebsite.nsf/wpg_url/Resources-Research-Index/$file/EthnicDiversity.pdf |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2008-10-14 |issn=1173-7166 |isbn=0-478-09244-X |accessdate=2009-09-19 }}</ref> The 1991 and 2006 New Zealand census reports about 2800 Bahá'ís<ref name="census" /> though the 1996 census listed just over 3100 Bahá'ís.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2001/5677.htm | title = International Religious Freedom Report - New Zealand | date = 26 October 2001 | accessdate = 2009-09-19| author = Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor | publisher = United States State Department}}</ref> The [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] (relying mostly on the [[World Christian Encyclopedia]]) estimated some 7400 Bahá'ís in 2005.<ref name="WCE-05" /> There are more than 65 local Bahá’í communities around New Zealand, the large city communities have hundreds of members and assemblies, while some rural areas having groups of just two or three Bahá'ís.<ref name="communities">{{cite web | title = The local Bahá'í community | work = New Zealand Community | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of New Zealand | url = http://www.bahai.org.nz/what_is_bahai/NZ_local.html | doi = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> About 46 are full-fledged assemblies.<ref name="Kapiti" /> The religion was called a "mainstream religion" by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].<ref>{{cite thesis
| author=Carrie Moore
 | title = Spiritual Experiences and Environmentalism of Recreational Users in the Marine Environment: New Zealand Surfers and Scuba Divers
 | page =22
 | publisher =Natural Resource Management and Ecological Engineering at Lincoln University
 | location = Christchurch, New Zealand
 | date =2011
 | url = http://hdl.handle.net/10182/3881 
| accessdate = Sep 10, 2015}}</ref>

==== Well known individuals ====

The Bahá´í Association For the Arts and its publication ''Arts Dialogue'' has produced a lists of New Zealand Bahá'í artists, reviews of the shows and articles published dealing with New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web | title = Aotearoa / New Zealand | work = external LINKS | publisher = The Bahá´í Association For the Arts | url = http://bahai-library.org/bafa/nz.htm | doi = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> The national assembly posted profiles of some Bahá'ís in 2011.<ref>{{cite web
 | title =Profiles of some New Zealand Bahá'ís
 | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of New Zealand
 | date = 2011
 | url =http://www.bahai.org.nz/new-zealand-bahais/profiles-of-some-new-zealand-bahais/ 
 | accessdate = Sep 10, 2015 }}</ref>

* [[Barry Crump]] was a writer of semi-autobiographical comic novels who travelled widely and became a Bahá'í about 1982.<ref>{{cite news | last = Reid | first = Tony | title = 'Crump Flags It Away' | newspaper = New Zealand Listener | location = Wellington, N. Z. | pages = 21–22, 25, 26 | publisher = | date = 20 November 1982 | url =}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = | first = | editor-last = Robinson | editor-first = Roger | editor2-last = Wattie | editor2-first = Nelson | title = The Oxford companion to New Zealand literature | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 1998 | location = | url = http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/Writers/Profiles/Crump,%20Barry | isbn = 978-0-19-558348-9}}</ref>
* Sheryl Davis works for a charitable trust focused on promoting economic development and tourism in the northern part of the country.<ref>{{cite web | title = Sheryl Davis | work = Profiles of Bahá'ís | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of New Zealand | url = http://www.bahai.org.nz/what_is_bahai/NZ_profiles9.html | doi = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref>
* [[Russell Garcia (composer)|Russell Garcia]] - Garcia is from [[Oakland, California]] and is a composer who has worked with major Hollywood artists and producers.<ref name="rainbold">[http://www.cdbaby.com/rainbolt3 Charmed Life: Shaynee Rainbolt Sings Russell Garcia] Liner Notes - This Bio Was approved by Russell Garcia and Gina Garcia in connection to their collaboration on Charmed Life: Shaynee Rainbolt SINGS Russell Garcia</ref> Garcia and his wife Gina have been members of the [[Bahá'í Faith]] since 1955.<ref name="coleman">{{cite web| title = Russell Garcia | work = The Time Machine Project | publisher = Don Coleman | url = http://www.colemanzone.com/Time_Machine_Project/r_garcia.htm | doi = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> In 1966 they set sail and ended up in the south Pacific when some musicians from [[Auckland, New Zealand]] invited Russell to do some live concerts, radio and television shows and to lecture at the various universities around the country on behalf of the New Zealand Broadcasting Commission and Music Trades Association. Russell, finished with his lectures and concerts and on advice of friends, drove up to the [[Bay of Islands]] in the north of [[North Island]] where they live.<ref name="rainbold" />
* Heather Simpson is a District Court judge, enrolled in the Bahá'í community in 1983.<ref>{{cite web | title = Heather Simpson | work = Profiles of Bahá'ís | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of New Zealand | url = http://www.bahai.org.nz/what_is_bahai/NZ_profiles5.html | doi = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref>
* [[Murray Robert Smith]] was a member of the New Zealand Parliament from 1972 to 1975. He later enrolled in the Bahá’í community and served on the national governing body for two years before he and his wife, Miette, began a period of service at the Bahá’í World Centre in Haifa, Israel, which lasted from 1994 to 2007. At the Bahá’í World Centre, Murray served as Deputy Secretary General of the [[Bahá'í International Community]], a role centred on developing the Bahá’í community's contributions to wider society.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081010194342/http://www.bahai.org.nz/Bahai_Institutions_and_Governance_Booklet.PDF Bahá’í Institutions AND Global Governance] An address given at the fiftieth anniversary celebrations of the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá’ís of New Zealand, on 28 April 2007. By [[Murray Robert Smith|Murray Smith]]</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Dewes | first = Haydon | last2 = Palmer | first2 = Rebecca | title = Twenty New Zealanders in Haifa | newspaper = The Dominion Post | location = | publisher = | date = 31 July 2006 | url = http://bahaisonline.net/index.php?Itemid=2&id=466&option=com_content&task=view | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Halle | first = Charlotte | title = Lots of parties, a war, some bad press and an astounding garden terrace | newspaper = | location = | publisher = | url = http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/815299.html | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref> Note government service is not proscribed,<ref>see for example Greg Zemke-Smith who both works in government and is a Bahá'í - {{cite web|url=http://www.register.charities.govt.nz/CharitiesRegister/ViewCharity?accountId=bc5d1665-0e31-dd11-8f7f-0015c5f3da29|title=Spiritual Assembly Of The Baha'is Of Wellington|year=2014|work=Charity Summary|publisher=Charities Commission|accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref> just partisan politics.
* [[Ken Zemke]] - Zemke was a freelance film editor working in Hollywood in 1972 when he became a Bahá'í after working on comedy TV series such as ''[[Hogan's Heroes]]'' and eventually won an Emmy in 1974, for an episode in the series ''[[Medical Story TV Series]]''. However he and his wife soon moved to New Zealand in 1981 where he continued work in movie production - winning New Zealand ''Guild of Film and Television'' award for best editing for [[Came a Hot Friday]] while continuing to be involved with documentaries and projects associated with the Bahá'í Faith through individual initiative or commissioned as well as his own ongoing project - ''Bahá'í on Air''.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Zemke | first = Ken | author-link = Ken Zemke | title = Ken Zemke film, video editor, New Zealand | journal = Arts Dialogue | volume = 2002 | issue = November | date = November 2002 | url =http://bahai-library.com/bafa/z/zemkek.htm }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Ken Zemke | work = Profiles of Bahá'ís | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of New Zealand | url = http://www.bahai.org.nz/what_is_bahai/NZ_profiles4.html | doi = | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref>

