{{Bahá'í sidebar}}
The '''Bahá'í Faith in the Marshall Islands''' begins after 1916 with a mention by [[`Abdu'l-Bahá]], then head of the religion, that Bahá'ís should take the religion there.<ref name="tab1">{{cite book |author = `Abdu'l-Bahá |authorlink = `Abdu'l-Bahá |year = 1991 |title = Tablets of the Divine Plan |edition = Paperback |publisher = Bahá'í Publishing Trust |location = Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn = 0-87743-233-3 |url =http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/ab/TDP/tdp-7.html.iso8859-1#pg41 | pages = 40–42 |origyear = 1916-17}}</ref> The first Bahá'í to [[Pioneering (Bahá'í)|pioneer]] there arrived in August 1954<ref name="Atwater">{{Cite journal | first = Janet | last = Ruhe-Schoen | title = An Enchantment of the Heart - A Portrait of Marcia Steward, Knight of Bahá’u’lláh, First Bahá’í Pioneer to Chile and the Marshall Islands | work = The Chilean Temple Initiative | year = 2007 | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Baha'is of the United States | url = http://www.chilean-temple.org/images/stories/Early%20Baha/%27is/an_enchantment_of_the_heart.pdf | postscript = <!--None--> }}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> however she could only stay until March 1955. Nevertheless, with successive pioneers and converts the first Bahá'í [[Local Spiritual Assembly]] in 1967 in [[Majuro]].<ref name="first">{{cite magazine | title = First Local Spiritual Assembly of…|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=January 1968 |issue = 442 | page =18 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm }}</ref> The community continued to grow and in 1977 elected its first [[National Spiritual Assembly]].<ref name="ABB">{{Cite journal| last = Hassall | first = Graham | title =H. Colllis Featherstone | journal =Australian Bahá'í Bulletin | volume = October | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of Australia |location = | year = 1990 | url = http://bahai-library.com/asia-pacific/featherstone.htm |accessdate =25 July 2010}}</ref> Before 1992 the Bahá'ís began to operate state schools under contract with the government.<ref name="hassal1">{{Cite book | first = Hassall | last = Graham |author2-link = | editor-last = Rubinstein | editor-first = Donald H. | contribution = Pacific Baha'i Communities 1950-1964 |contribution-url = http://bahai-library.com/hassall_bahai_pacific | title = Pacific History: Papers from the 8th Pacific History Association Conference | year = 1992 | pages = 73–95 | publisher = University of Guam Press & Micronesian Area Research Center, Guam |url= | postscript = . }}</ref> Middle estimates of the Bahá'í population are just over 1,000, or 1.50% in 2000.<ref name="adhere2000">{{cite encyclopedia | title = Top 20 Largest National Baha'i Populations | encyclopedia = Adherents.com| publisher =Adherents.com | url =http://www.adherents.com/largecom/com_bahai.html | year = 2008 | id = | accessdate =18 November 2008 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081019165843/http://www.adherents.com/largecom/com_bahai.html| archivedate= 19 October 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

==Early days==

===`Abdu'l-Bahá's Tablets of the Divine Plan===
`Abdu'l-Bahá, head of the religion from 1892 to 1921, mentioned the Marshall Islands among the places Bahá'ís should take the religion to. He wrote a series of letters, or [[tablets (religious)|tablets]], to the followers of the religion in the [[United States]] in 1916-1917; these letters were compiled together in the book titled [[Tablets of the Divine Plan]]. The seventh of the tablets mentioned taking the Bahá'í Faith to the Marshall Islands and was written on 11 April 1916, but was delayed in being presented in the United States until 1919 &mdash; after the end of [[World War I]] and the [[Spanish flu]]. These tablets were translated and presented by [[Mirza Ahmad Sohrab]] on 4 April 1919, and published in [[Star of the West (Bahá'í magazine)|Star of the West]] magazine on 12 December 1919.<ref>{{cite book |last = Abbas | first = 'Abdu'l-Bahá |others=Mirza Ahmad Sohrab (trans. and comments) | title = Tablets, Instructions and Words of Explanation |date=April 1919 | url = http://bahai-library.com/abdulbaha_tablets_instructions_explanation}}</ref>

<blockquote>(Tablet 7) "A party speaking their languages, severed, holy, sanctified and filled with the love of God, must turn their faces to and travel through the three great island groups of the Pacific Ocean — [[Polynesia]], [[Micronesia]] and [[Melanesia]], and the islands attached to these groups, such as New Guinea, Borneo, Java, Sumatra, Philippine Islands, Solomon Islands, Fiji Islands, New Hebrides, Loyalty Islands, New Caledonia, Bismarck Archipelago, Ceram, Celebes, Friendly Islands, Samoa Islands, Society Islands, Caroline Islands, Low Archipelago, Marquesas, Hawaiian Islands, Gilbert Islands, Moluccas, [[Marshall Islands]], Timor and the other islands. With hearts overflowing with the love of God, with tongues commemorating the mention of God, with eyes turned to the Kingdom of God, they must deliver the glad tidings of the manifestation of the Lord of Hosts to all the people. Know ye of a certainty that whatever gathering ye enter, the waves of the Holy Spirit are surging over it, and the heavenly grace of the Blessed Beauty encompasseth that gathering."<ref name="tab1"/></blockquote>

===Beginnings===
Marcia Steward (later de Matamores Atwater), was a [[pioneering (Bahá'í)|pioneer]] and named a [[Knights of Bahá'u'lláh|Knight of Bahá’u’lláh]] for being the first to move to the Marshall Islands. Steward was born in Pasadena, California in 1904, and embraced the religion in 1938 and was eager to pioneer before the conclusion of the first Seven Year Plan (1937–1944) of [[Shoghi Effendi]], who was named `Abdu'l-Bahá's successor. First she moved to Santiago de Chile. She continued to serve across Latin America for a number of years as plans proceeded for the religion.<ref name="Atwater"/> See [[Bahá'í Faith in Chile]], [[Bahá'í Faith in Costa Rica]].<ref name="alamb">{{cite book | last = Lamb | first = Artemus |title = The Beginnings of the Bahá'í Faith in Latin America:Some Remembrances, English Revised and Amplified Edition | publisher = M L VanOrman Enterprises |date=November 1995 | location = West Linn, OR | url =http://bahai-library.com/lamb_bahai_latin_america}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first = Shoghi |last = Effendi |authorlink = Shoghi Effendi |origyear = |year = 1947 |title = Messages to America |publisher = Bahá'í Publishing Committee |location = Wilmette, Illinois, USA |oclc =  5806374|url =http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/se/MA/ma-16.html.iso8859-1?query=Appeal |page=6 |isbn = 0-87743-145-0 }}</ref> By July 1947 Atwater was appointed secretary of the Central American Teaching Committee<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Latin American Administration Develops |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1947 | issue = 197 | page =3 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm}}</ref> with one of its goals to facilitate a shift in the balance of roles from North American guidance and Latin cooperation to Latin guidance and North American cooperation.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Historical Background of the Panama Temple|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1972 | issue = 493 | page =2 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm}}</ref> The process was well underway by 1950 and was to be enforced about 1953. While she was deciding where to serve next a cable from Shoghi Effendi arrived asking Atwater to try to get to the Marshall Islands sometime between 1 April and 2 May 1954. His cable reached Atwater on 16 April and by 20 April she was in Washington DC. Immediately after World War II the islands were administered for about 6 years by the United States Navy. When the Trusteeships under the United Nations were formed, the Marshall Islands became part of the Trusteeship of the Pacific (which included the Caroline, and Mariana Islands as well as the Marshall Islands). The United States was given the authority to administer this Trusteeship by the United Nations. The Marshall Islands were the site of [[:Category:U.S. nuclear test sites|nuclear bomb tests]], the Marshall Islands were tightly closed to any guests unconnected with government work. At the time she had a contract with a publisher and hoped to be self-sufficient after finishing her book. By 9 May she informed [[Horace Holley (Bahá'í)|Horace Holley]] that she had permission to enter the islands and was awaiting her Navy security clearance. Atwater was able to secure a visa to travel there because of excellent connections in Washington D.C., and got her original three-month pass renewed because of the same contacts. Maintaining the appearance of wealth and ease which accompanied her family's position in the U.S., she was actually, by the time she went to the Marshalls, completely without independent income, and was deputized by the United States National Spiritual Assembly with some help from the National Spiritual Assembly of Central America. In July 1954 she left Hawaii, finally, for Japan, and then sailed from Kobe to the Marshall Islands, arriving in [[Majuro]], capital and largest city of the Republic of the Marshall Islands, on August 7.

While there she was invited to a reception in honor of a visiting U.S. congressman from Colorado where she recited, upon request, some of her "poetry of Majuro," after which the congressman asked for copies. Marcia wrote to Virginia Breaks in the [[Caroline Islands]] that most of her good friends in the Marshalls were Catholic or Jesuit priests, remarking, "this is probably natural, since I lived in a Latin-American Catholic environment for so many years." Breaks said that Atwater seemed to "greatly enjoy" her time on the islands, and "she was apparently given government housing." Marcia hoped to stay on in the islands although she was very ill during her last two months there, but she was not given another permit. She was able to stay until March 1955. During that time she taught the religion, traveled to various atolls, fulfilled some press commitments which were subject to the District Commissioner's censor but which had, in the end, been helpful in securing her visa; and she tried to get some Bahá’í information translated into Marshallese. The nature of her illness is unknown, as is the story of all her activities there, since the report she wrote was lost and she evidently never had the strength to re-write it. After leaving the islands she suffered from a debilitating skin ailment, of which she wrote, "A terrible affliction has me almost ready to be locked up: I am quite horrible to behold...." She felt her skin problem was caused by radiation burns from atomic testing on the Marshalls, but this could never be proved, and she tried unsuccessfully to collect compensation from the U.S. government.

The Marshall Islands, vacated for several months when it became necessary for Atwater to leave, was replaced by another Bahá'í pioneer, Betty Klaas, from Honolulu by August 1956.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Intercontinental Committees; Asia ENROLL MANY BELIEVERS IN PACIFIC ISLANDS |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1956 | issue = 306 | page =7 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm}}</ref> By 1960 there were no pioneer Bahá'ís<ref>{{cite magazine | title = South Pacific|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1960 |issue = 353 | page =6 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm }}</ref> but by 1964 there is mention of a group of Bahá'ís there.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Progress of the Nine Year Plan News from the World Center|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1964 | issue = 405 | page =1 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm }}</ref> The first [[Local Spiritual Assembly]] of the Bahá'ís of Majuro was elected 21 April 1967. This is also the first Local Spiritual Assembly to be formed in the Trust Territory of Micronesia. Its members were Jack Peter, Elsie Heran, Ninam Reran, Brad Hollinger (pioneer), Kim Lang (pioneer), Tataka Arawatau, Betra Heran, Harlan Lang (pioneer) and Pencil Heran.<ref name="first"/> In 1972 a regional spiritual assembly of the North West Pacific Ocean was based in [[Pohnpei]] covering the Caroline, Marshall and Mariana Islands.<ref>[http://bahai-library.com/hassall_asia-pacific_spiritual_axisBahá'í Communities in the Asia-Pacific Performing Common Theology and Cultural Diversity on a 'Spiritual Axis'] by Graham Hassall and William Barnes.</ref>

A second local assembly was elected in "Laura" in 1975.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Northwest Pacific Ocean 20th, 21st Local Assemblies formed|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1975 | issue = 537 | page =17 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm }}</ref> In 1976 the first spiritual assembly on Santo Island, in the [[Kwajalein Atoll]], was announced January 1. All the teachers involved in the formation of this assembly were Micronesians. The activity evolved under the direction of the national teaching committee of the Marshall Islands, with the help of the Spiritual Assembly of [[Ebeye Island]] of the same atoll.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Around the World; North West Pacific Ocean Santo Island forms first Assembly|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1976 | issue = 542 | page =12 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm }}</ref>

==Growth across the nation==
Following international conferences on the promulgation of the religion in Hong Kong, 26–30 November 1975 and Auckland, New Zealand, 19–22 January 1976 a Marshallese conference was held later in January.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Around the World; North West Pacific Ocean Santo Island forms first Assembly|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1976 | issue = 545 | page =5 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm }}</ref> In March 1977 four Bahá'í communities gathered and had a picnic to discuss the upcoming first National Convention and the importance of [[Bahá'í administration#Elected institutions|Local Spiritual Assembly elections]]. Thirty-five Bahá'ís and their children were present.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Around the World; Marshall Islands - First National Convention picnic topic|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1977 | issue = 553 | page =16 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm }}</ref>
{{Location map+|Marshall islands|float=right|width=300|caption=Bahá'í communities of the [[Marshall Islands]] by the mid-1980s|places=
{{Location map~|Marshall islands|mark=Red star.svg|label=[[Majuro]]|position=bottom|lat=7.069|long=171.28}}
{{Location map~|Marshall islands|label=[[Ujelang Atoll]]|position=right|lat=9.82|long=160.9}}
{{Location map~|Marshall islands|label=[[Mili Atoll]]|position=bottom|lat=6.13|long=171.92}}
{{Location map~|Marshall islands|label=[[Lae Atoll]]|position=left|lat=8.94|long=166.24}}
{{Location map~|Marshall islands|label=[[Ajeltake]]|position=top|lat=7.08|long=171.13}}
{{Location map~|Marshall islands|label=[[Kwajalein Atoll]]|position=bottom|lat=8.72|long=167.73}}
{{Location map~|Marshall islands|label=[[Enewetak Atoll]]|position=right|lat=11.5|long=162.3}}
}}
[[Hand of the Cause]] [[Collis Featherstone]] represented the [[Universal House of Justice]] as witness to the convention and election<ref name="ABB"/> in April when the [[National Spiritual Assembly]] of the Marshall Islands was elected.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Mariana Bahá’í Community (History) | work = Official Website of the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of the Mariana Islands| publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of the Mariana Islands | url = http://marianas.bahai.org/community.html | accessdate = 25 July 2010}}</ref> Among the national assembly's first goals assigned by the Universal House of Justice was a goal to "Open the remaining major islands of the Marshalls to the Faith and greatly increase the number of believers."<ref name="islands">{{Cite web | last = Universal House of Justice | first = Department of the Secretariat |authorlink = | title = Marshall Islands population statistics | work = | publisher = Baha'i Academic Library Online | date =23 June 1996 | url = http://bahai-library.com/uhj_marshall_islands_population | accessdate =25 July 2010}}</ref> By the end of 1977 two new assemblies are in [[Ajeltake]] and Arno Arno Lukej which were elected bringing the total in the Marshall Islands to nine.<ref>{{cite magazine |title = Around the World; Marshall Islands -Traveling teacher brings Faith to islanders|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1977| issue = 561 | page =16 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm }}</ref>

In February 1979 the National Spiritual Assembly of the Marshall Islands reports "The major islands that are uninhabited: Toka, Ailinginae, Rongdrik, Jemo, Bikini, Erkub, Bokak, Bikar." In the same report, Rongelap Atoll is listed as having a Bahá'í group, [[Ujelang Atoll]] is shown as an isolated Bahá'í and [[Enewetak Atoll]] as well is shown to have a group.<ref name="islands"/> In March the Department of Secretariat at the [[Bahá'í World Centre]] writes to the national assembly saying, "It is noted that there are only two major inhabited islands not yet open to the Faith -- Mejit and Ailuk, and it is hoped these will soon be opened."<ref name="islands"/> By the summer of 1979 there were 15 more local assemblies, 42 localities, a temple site, endowment land, three local centers, and two revised translations of a prayer book.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =VictoryMessages - The Baha'I world resounds with the glorious news of Five Year Plan victories; Australasia; Marshall Islands|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1979 | issue = 581 | page =9 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm |issn=0043-8804}}</ref>

In August 1983 the national assembly report states "Atolls which have no population and therefore are not to be considered under any teaching plan are as follows: Ailingae, Bikar, Bikini, Bokaak (Taongi), Erikub, Jemo, Knox, Rongerik, and Taja." A note is appended by the national assembly to this same report reads: "Note: Though one of the larger islands of the M.I. atolls, Rongelap is largely radioactive, with no population."<ref>For more information on movements of populations and drifts of radiation see {{Cite journal | last = Jamir | first = Vinson |title = the South Pacific Islands: Economic, Political and Legal Interactions | journal = LLM theses |page=172 | publisher = University of Georgia School of Law | location = | year = 1983 | url = http://digitalcommons.law.uga.edu/stu_llm/107/ | accessdate =25 July 2010}}</ref> A second note, in reference to Ujelang Atoll, reads: "Note: For a time uninhabited, there is a report some people may have returned."<ref name="islands"/> A [[former Peace Corps]] member who had worked on [[Lae Atoll]] in 1969-71 as an elementary school teacher returned in 1984 as a Bahá'í and managed to introduce the religion on a few atolls where no natives had yet joined the religion. She stayed in the Marshall Islands as a pioneer until 2000.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Marshal Islands - A pioneer returns ''home'' to Lae Atoll|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1985 | issue = 649 |pages=10–11 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm | issn=0043-8804}}</ref>

===Multiplying interests accelerate===
Since its inception the religion has had involvement in [[socio-economic development]] beginning by giving greater freedom to women,<ref name="iranhistory">{{cite web |last=Momen |first = Moojan |title = History of the Baha'i Faith in Iran | work = draft "A Short Encyclopedia of the Baha'i Faith" | publisher = Bahai-library.com |url =http://bahai-library.com/momen_encyclopedia_iran#9.%20Social%20and%20economic%20development | format = | doi = |accessdate =16 October 2009}}</ref> promulgating the promotion of female education as a priority concern,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Kingdon | first = Geeta Gandhi | title= Education of women and socio-economic development | journal = Baha'i Studies Review | volume = 7 |issue = 1 | year = 1997 |url =http://bahai-library.com/kingdon_education_women_development | postscript = . }}</ref> and that involvement was given practical expression by creating schools, agricultural coops, and clinics.<ref name="iranhistory"/> The religion entered a new phase of activity when a message of the [[Universal House of Justice]] dated 20 October 1983 was released.<ref>{{cite journal |title= The Baha'i Faith 1957–1988: A Survey of Contemporary Developments | first = Moojan | last = Momen |author2=Smith, Peter | year = 1989 |url =http://bahai-library.com/momen_smith_developments_1957-1988 |volume = 19 | journal = Religion | pages=63–91 |doi= 10.1016/0048-721X(89)90077-8|postscript= .}}</ref> Bahá'ís were urged to seek out ways, compatible with the [[Bahá'í teachings]], in which they could become involved in the social and economic development of the communities in which they lived. Worldwide in 1979 there were 129 officially recognized Bahá'í socio-economic development projects. By 1987, the number of officially recognized development projects had increased to 1482. In the Marshall Islands a management team composed of Bahá'ís as requested by the national government, operated 7 public elementary schools under contract with the government.<ref name="hassal-pacific">{{Cite news | last = Hassall | first = Graham | title = Bahá'í Faith in the Asia Pacific Issues and Prospects | periodical = Bahá'í Studies Review | volume=06 | pages = 1–10 |year = 1996 | url = http://bahai-library.com/hassall_bahai_asia-pacific_issues |postscript = . }}</ref> Following the growth of the institutions the organizational impact of the Bahá'ís became more well known starting in the mid-1980s in the Marshall Islands. Seventy Bahá'ís from 19 communities attended the eighth national conference on the progress of the religion in winter 1984 at the national center. Presentations were made on the history of the religion, the role of Bahá'í youth, laws, consultation, living a Bahá'í life, goals of the current plans, and the Baha'i Faith and the Bible and plans were announced for a national Baha'i women's conference.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = The World; Marshal Islands|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1985 | issue = 649 | page =13 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm | issn=0043-8804}}</ref> In July 1985 the Annual Statistical Report has a note on Ujelang as having a group with less than nine adult believers.<ref name="islands"/> In January 1986 a national Bahá'í Youth conference was held in Majuro to which 200 children and adults attended the potluck feast followed by 30 youth staying for the workshops.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The World; Shown here are some of the youth… |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1986 | issue = 662 | page =14 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm | issn=0043-8804}}</ref> In August Bahá'ís from more than 20 communities gathered at the Bahá'í National Center for a national peace conference where one of the guest speakers was A.D. Tennekone, Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the Republic of the Marshall Islands.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The World; Baha'ls from more than 20 communities…|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1986 | issue = 668 | page =17 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm |issn=0043-8804}}</ref> In October national assembly hosted an [[International Year of Peace]] dinner for the President and other government officials in Majuro as well as a [[United Nations Day]] public peace program in [[Mili Atoll]].<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The World; Marshall Islands|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1987 | issue = 678 | page =17 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm | issn=0043-8804}}</ref> In August 1987 the national assembly locality report notes Enewetak and Ujelang Atolls are listed as having Bahá'ís.<ref name="islands"/> The first Marshall Islander went on [[Bahá'í pilgrimage]] in February 1987.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The World; Baha'is from more than 20 communities…|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1987 |issue = 676 | page =16 | url =http://www.teachingandprojects.com/meansandmaterials.htm | issn=0043-8804}}</ref>

==Modern community==
From at least 2001 to 2007 the national assembly ran a website<ref>{{Cite web|title=Archived Results from 1 January 1996 - latest |work= |publisher=Internet Archive Wayback Machines |url=http://www.mh.bahai.org/ |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010420000357/http://www.mh.bahai.org/main.cfm?doc=31&comm=18&lang=1&action=normal |archivedate=20 April 2001 |accessdate=29 August 2016}}</ref> which hosted [[Marshallese language]] [[Bahá'í literature]]<ref>{{Cite web | title = Jar an Bahá’í| work = Official Website of the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of the Marshall Ialands | publisher = Bahá'í Community of the Marshall Islands| year = 2002 | url = http://www.mh.bahai.org/main.cfm?doc=146&comm=18&lang=1&action=normal | accessdate =25 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020610201540/http://www.mh.bahai.org/main.cfm?doc=146&comm=18&lang=1&action=normal |archivedate=10 June 2002}}</ref> and [[Ruhi Institute]] books online.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Mour inm Mij (Ruhi Buk 1) | work = Official Website of the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of the Marshall Ialands | publisher = Bahá'í Community of the Marshall Islands | year = 2002 | url =http://www.mh.bahai.org/main.cfm?doc=150&comm=18&lang=1&action=normal | accessdate=25 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020601110915/http://www.mh.bahai.org/main.cfm?doc=150&comm=18&lang=1&action=normal |archivedate=1 June 2002}}</ref> Dominic Tabuaka represented the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of the Marshall Islands attended the 50th anniversary of the [[Bahá'í Faith in Kiribati]].<ref name="50th">{{Cite news| last = Bahá'í International Community | first = | author-link = Bahá'í International Community |title = Sailing in for a jubilee |newspaper=Bahá'í World News Service | date =4 March 2004 |url =http://news.bahai.org/story/301| postscript = .}}</ref> And Bahá'ís from the Marshall Islands attended the regional conference of Bahá'ís in the Philippines in 2008.<ref>{{cite web | author = Bahá'í International Community | title = Bahá´ís of the Philippines - Regional Conference-Conference Update |work= | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of the Philippines | date =7 December 2008 | url =http://www.bahai.ph/conference-update.php#middle | accessdate =21 February 2009 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090326064120/http://bahai.ph/conference-update.php| archivedate= 26 March 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

===Relations with Marshallese government===
The Bahá'ís have had a long positive relationship with the government. [[Amata Kabua]], then President of the Marshall Islands, was a government leader who has a close relationship with Bahá'í institutions nationally and internationally. In his address at the opening of the UN General Assembly in October 1991 President Kabua called for "a new and comprehensive vision of a global society, supported by a new system of values. This recognition does not imply the abandonment of legitimate loyalties, the suppression of cultural diversity, nor the abolition of national autonomy. It calls for a wider loyalty, for a far higher aspiration than has thus far animated human affairs."<ref name="hassal-pacific"/><ref>For similarity of language, consider:
*{{cite book |first=Shoghi |last=Effendi |authorlink= Shoghi Effendi |year= 1938 |title= The World Order of Bahá’u’lláh |publisher=Bahá'í Publishing Trust |location=Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn= 0-87743-231-7 |page=41 |url= http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/se/WOB/wob-21.html.utf8?query=It%20can%20conflict%20with%20no%20legitimate%20allegiances&action=highlight#gr1 }}
*{{cite book |author= Universal House of Justice |authorlink= Universal House of Justice |year= 1986 |title= The Promise of World Peace|publisher= Oneworld |location=London, UK |isbn= 1-85168-002-0| page = 10 |url= http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/uhj/PWP/pwp-4.html.utf8?query=It%20can%20conflict%20with%20no%20legitimate%20allegiances&action=highlight#gr5 }}
</ref> He also delivered the keynote address to the ''Turning Point for All Nations'' seminar held at the [[Bahá'í International Community]]'s offices in October 1995.<ref>{{Cite web| title = UN 50: Bahá'ís Commemorate the Fiftieth Anniversary of the United Nations | work = | publisher = Bahá'í International Community | url = http://info.bahai.org/article-1-9-2-13.html | accessdate =25 July 2010}}</ref> In the summer of 2000 the Bahá'ís held an ''Ocean of Light Conference'' which was biggest Bahá'í event ever up to that time in the country and was attended by [[Kessai Note]], the next president of the Marshall Islands, along with over 250 Bahá'ís from across the Pacific.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Ocean of Light Conference 2000 | work = Official Website of the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of the Marshall Ialands | publisher = Bahá'í Community of the Marshall Islands | year = 2001 | url = http://www.mh.bahai.org/main.cfm?doc=35&comm=18&lang=1&action=normal | accessdate =19 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010420001312/http://www.mh.bahai.org/main.cfm?doc=35&comm=18&lang=1&action=normal |archivedate=20 April 2001}}</ref> 
President Kessai Note, and his wife, Mary Note, also paid an official visit to the [[Bahá'í World Centre]] on 1 December 2005.<ref>{{Cite journal
| title = President of the Marshall Islands visits the Bahá'í World Centre | journal = One Country | volume = 17 | issue = 03 | publisher = Bahá'í International Community | location = Haifa, Israel | date = October–December 2005 | url =http://www.onecountry.org/e173/e17303as_Marshall_Islands_Pres_story.htm| accessdate =25 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = Head of state visits Baha'i World Centre| newspaper = Bahá'í World News Service| publisher = Bahá'í International Community | location = Haifa, Israel| date = 7 December 2005 | url =http://news.bahai.org/story/410| accessdate =25 July 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://news.bahai.org/story/410 Head of state visits Baha'i World Centre] 7 December 2005</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = RMI Presidential Visits | newspaper =Yokwe.net | publisher = Yokew.net |url=http://www.yokwe.net/index.php?set_albumName=album101&name=gallery&include=view_album.php| accessdate =25 July 2010}}</ref>

===Focus to the society===
By 1992 the Bahá'ís operate state schools under contract with the government.<ref name="hassal1"/>
In 2003 a Bahá'í with the main goal of helping the rural population established a project which he sees as an extension of his commitment to the promotion of social and economic development — a commitment that stems from his practice of the Bahá’í Faith.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Bahá'í International Community | title = Vanuatu Mechanic Going to Town on tank of Coconut oil | journal =Pacific Islands Report | publisher = Pacific Islands Development Program/East-West Center | location = Port Vila, Vanuatu | date =August 2003 | url = http://166.122.164.43/archive/2003/August/08-21-feature.htm| accessdate =16 August 2010}}</ref>

In 2007 The [[Commission on Sustainable Development]] held sessions in relation to CSD-15. One attracted 90 people to hear six panelists. The event was chaired by Tahirih Naylow and sponsored by the Bahá'í International Community<ref>{{Cite web | title = The Ethical Dimensions of Climate Change | work = Statements and Reports → Archives | publisher = Bahá'í International Community | url =http://www.bic.org/statements-and-reports/featured/the-ethical-dimensions-of-climate-change | accessdate=25 May 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527001355/http://bic.org/statements-and-reports/featured/the-ethical-dimensions-of-climate-change| archivedate=27 May 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last = Rowa | first = Aenet |title = Marshall Islands Focuses on Climate Change at CSD-15 Meetings|newspaper =Yokwe Online |publisher= |date=13 May 2007 |url=http://www.yokwe.com/index.php?name=News&file=article&sid=1767&theme=Printer |accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref> with the UN Permanent Missions of Tuvalu and of the Marshall Islands and a number of other UN and academic organizations.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Posas |first=Paula J. |title = ESEP Essay Content Winner in Philosophy/Religious Studies- Roles of religion and ethics in addressing climate change |journal = Ethics in Science and Environmental Politics |volume =2007 |issue = 31–49 | location = | date = 10 December 2007 | url =http://www.int-res.com/articles/esep/2007/E80.pdf |issn= |doi=10.3354/esep00080 |accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref> Enele Sopoaga, former Ambassador and Permanent Representative of Tuvalu to the UN, opened the session, noting that reports suggest that for islands such as his as well as other atoll states: Maldives, Marshall Islands, and Kiribati, scenarios for the future include “total extinction.”

In 2009<ref>{{Cite web | first = Alissa | last = Emmel | title = Climate Ethics Session Report – Part II | work = The International Environment Forum: E-Conference 2009 | publisher = International Environment Forum | date = 26 August 2009 | url =http://iefconf2009.wordpress.com/page/2/ | accessdate =25 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | first = Alissa | last = Emmel | title = Climate Ethics | work = The International Environment Forum: E-Conference 2009 | publisher = International Environment Forum | date = 15 August 2009 |url =http://iefconf2009.wordpress.com/2009/07/30/climate-ethics/ |accessdate =25 July 2010}}</ref> and 2010 people attended follow-up meetings on the theme at sessions of a conference sponsored in part by the International Environment Forum, a Bahá'í inspired organization.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Highlights| work = Official Website of the International Environment Forum | publisher = International Environment Forum | date = 12 November 2009 | url = http://www.bcca.org/ief/home.htm|accessdate =25 July 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100711022537/http://www.bcca.org/ief/home.htm| archivedate= 11 July 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The session was given by two Bahá'ís: Carol Curtis and Tahirih Naylor, of the Bahá'í International Community. Naylor considered the macro level, looking at the importance of including ethics in the discussion of climate change and the Bahá’í contribution to the climate change discourse, Curtis focused on the micro level, specifically the threat that climate change poses to the Marshall Islands. Curtis has lived on the Lea Atoll for more than 40 years.<ref>{{Cite web |title=IEF presenter Bios |work=The 13th Annual Conference of the International Environment Forum integrated into the 33rd Annual Conference of the Association for Baha'i Studies - North America on the theme Environments |publisher=International Environment Forum |date=10 January 2010 |url=http://iefworld.org/conf13prg.htm#IEF_PRESENTER_BIOS |accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref> She describes in some detail the environment and lifestyle on the islands, the population and the land area.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Curtis |first=Carol |title=Climate Ethics Presentation - Marshall Islands (description of powerpoint slides) |work=Climate Ethics Panel Discussion |publisher=International Environment Forum |date=25 August 2009 |url=https://iefconf2009.files.wordpress.com/2009/10/carol-curtis-marshall-islands-paper.doc |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121130052337/http://iefconf2009.files.wordpress.com/2009/10/carol-curtis-marshall-islands-paper.doc |dead-url=yes |archive-date=30 November 2012 |accessdate=25 July 2010 }}</ref>

===Demographics===
Estimates of the number of Bahá'ís in the Marshal Islands vary considerably. From 1983 to 1987 the percentage of Bahá'ís reported for the Marshall Islands, went from 2% to 11.5% according to Bahá'í sources. Similar growth rates are reported in some other Pacific nations.<ref name="hassal1"/> But as early as 2001 the US State Dept estimated the Bahá'ís at 0.6 percent or about 400.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2001/5620.htm International Religious Freedom Report 2001: Marshall Islands]. United States [[Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor]] (14 September 2001).</ref> However almost at the same time the 2000 [[World Christian Encyclopedia]] estimation of a Bahá'í population was just over 1,000, or 1.50%.<ref name="adhere2000"/>

