{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = G. B. Singh | image = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_date = | birth_name = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = [[Historian]], [[biographer]], [[columnist]] | genre = [[History]], [[Political Science]] | movement = [[Literary realism|Realism]] | net worth = ? | notableworks =[[Gandhi Behind the Mask of Divinity]], [[Gandhi Under Cross Examination]] | influences = [[Guru Gobind Singh]] | influenced = | website = | spouse = | children = |signature = }}
'''G.B. Singh''' is the author of ''[[Gandhi Behind the Mask of Divinity]]'', a biography of Mahatma Gandhi<ref name="kansas1"> {{cite news |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |date=January 2, 2005 |title=Gandhi as a racist doesn't add up |first=Katie |last=Volin |page=1 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.sikhspectrum.com/082004/gandhi_mask.htm Issue No.17, August 2004] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228114504/http://www.sikhspectrum.com/082004/gandhi_mask.htm |date=2007-12-28 }}</ref> and ''[[Gandhi Under Cross Examination]]''.<ref>[http://www.conspiracyculture.com/events_Gandhi.html Consipiracy Culture - Reviewing Gandhi Under Cross Examination]</ref>
==Career== A [[periodontist]], Singh served in the [[U.S. Army]] as a [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]], one of a small number of [[Sikh]]s allowed to retain articles of faith, grandfathered in after a change in policy in 1984 forbidding soldiers from exhibiting their religion with "conspicuous" clothing or style of hair or beard. He was one of few Sikhs with a turban in the U.S. Army.
Although Singh has retired from the U.S. Army, he is still actively involved in supporting rights for future Sikhs to keep their article of faiths in the military.<ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.army.mil/-news/2010/03/25/36339-sikh-soldiers-allowed-to-serve-retain-their-articles-of-faith/ |title=Sikh Soldiers allowed to serve, retain their articles of faith |accessdate=2011-01-18 }}</ref>
In an interview Singh said that he became interested in studying [[Hinduism]] while a student of [[political science]] at the [[University of Oklahoma]].<ref name="sikhspectrum"> {{cite web |url = http://www.sikhspectrum.com/082004/gbsingh_int.htm |title = Interview by Manbir Singh Chowdhary |accessdate = 2011-01-18 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100725192848/http://www.sikhspectrum.com/082004/gbsingh_int.htm |archivedate = 2010-07-25 |df = }}</ref> In 1983, while watching the film ''[[Gandhi (film)|Gandhi]]'' and after reading an article, ''The Gandhi Nobody Knows'' by [[Richard Grenier (newspaper columnist)|Richard Grenier]], he began his investigation into Gandhi's life, which led to the book ''[[Gandhi Behind the Mask of Divinity]]''.<ref name="sikhspectrum"/>
==Selected writings== *''Gandhi Behind the Mask of Divinity *''Gandhi Under Cross Examination
==Personal life== He has three daughters and a son. His family currently resides in Colorado.
