In [[Religion in ancient Rome|ancient Roman religion]] and [[Roman law|law]], the '''''auspicia maxima''''' (also ''maxima auspicia'') were the "greatest auspices," conferred on [[Executive Magistrates of the Roman Republic|senior magistrates]] who held ''[[imperium]]'': "''[[auspicium]]'' and ''imperium'' were the twin pillars of the magistrate's power" ''([[potestas]]''). Only magistrates who had ''auspicia maxima'' were entitled to begin a war and, if victorious, to celebrate a [[Roman triumph|triumph]].<ref>[[J. Rufus Fears]], "The Cult of Jupiter and Roman Imperial Ideology," ''Aufstieg under Nierdergang der römische Welt'' II.17.2 (1981), p. 13 [https://books.google.com/books?id=OvJZbE_eYmsC&pg=PA13&dq=%22maxima+auspicia%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=35#v=onepage&q=%22maxima%20auspicia%22&f=false online.]</ref> The ''auspicia maxima'' were reserved primarily for [[Roman consul|consuls]] and [[Roman censor|censors]], but these were two different types of auspices. Consuls and censors were not [[Collegium (ancient Rome)|colleagues]], and the censors lacked military auspices ''(auspicia militiae)''. [[Praetor]]s, however, held a form of ''auspicia maxima'' and could also lead an army, though their ''imperium'' was lesser than that of the consuls.<ref>[[T. Corey Brennan]], ''The Praetorship in the [[Roman Republic]]'' (Oxford University Press, 2000), vol. 1, pp. 55–58 [https://books.google.com/books?id=Jd8N4LTUv8YC&pg=PA56&dq=%22maxima+auspicia%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=3#v=onepage&q=%22maxima%20auspicia%22&f=false online.]</ref>

