{{about|the weekly newspaper published in New York City|text=You may be looking for the [[Washington Jewish Week]]}} {{COI|date=March 2015}} {{Infobox Newspaper | name = The Jewish Week | logo = | image = Jewishweek.jpg | caption = Front page | type = Weekly [[newspaper]] | format = [[Broadsheet]] | foundation = {{start date and age|1875}} | ceased publication = | price = | owners = | political position = | publisher = | editor = [[Gary Rosenblatt]] | circulation = 55,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/advertise/advertiser_information|title=Advertiser Information- The Jewish Week Media Group|website=The Jewish Week|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405222326/http://www.thejewishweek.com/advertise/advertiser_information|archivedate=2016-04-05|df=}}</ref> | staff = | politics = | headquarters = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]] | ISSN = | website = [http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/ jewishweek.timesofisrael.com] }}
'''''The Jewish Week''''' is a weekly independent community [[newspaper]] targeted towards the [[Jew]]ish community of the metropolitan New York City area.<ref name=":0" /> ''The Jewish Week'' covers news relating to the Jewish community in NYC. In March 2016, ''The Jewish Week'' announced its partnership with the online newspaper ''[[The Times of Israel]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jewish Week To Partner With Times Of Israel|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/jewish-week-to-partner-with-times-of-israel/|publisher=The Jewish Week|accessdate=24 January 2017|date=March 22, 2016}}</ref>
==Editorial staff== [[Gary Rosenblatt]] has been the [[Editing#Periodicals|editor]] and publisher since 1993.
==Awards== In 2016, ''The Jewish Week'' [http://www.deadlineclub.org/archives/4312 became a finalist for awards in two categories] by the Deadline Club, the New York City chapter of the Society of Professional Journalists, for its series on the battle to improve secular education in chasidic schools. The series was done in partnership with WNYC.
In 2000, Rosenblatt and the newspaper won the Casey Medal for Meritorious Journalism from the Journalism Center on Children & Families for the story "Stolen Innocence", an investigative report that uncovered allegations of decades of child abuse by a youth movement leader and high school principal, [[Baruch Lanner]]. The story was criticized by some in the Orthodox community for being "[[Lashon hara|malicious gossip]]".<ref name=":0">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C07E6D81538F933A25754C0A9669C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2 |title=Paper Seen as Villain in Abuse Accusations Against Rabbi |publisher=New York Times |date=July 10, 2000 |author= |accessdate=June 29, 2011}}</ref>
